# Clean Code (Java)

## Naming

- Reveal intent. Classes = nouns (`CreateUserUseCase`), methods = verbs (`confirmAccount`).
- No abbreviations or single letters (except loop indices). No Hungarian notation.
- Booleans read as predicates: `isActive`, `hasConfirmedEmail`.

## Methods & classes

- Small functions; do **one thing**. Prefer ≤ ~20 lines and few parameters (≤ 3 — use a command/record otherwise).
- One public responsibility per class (SRP). Split when a class grows multiple reasons to change.
- Avoid deep nesting — use early returns / guard clauses.

```java
// ✅ GOOD: guard clauses, single responsibility
public UserResponse execute(CreateUserCommand cmd) {
    if (cmd == null) throw new IllegalArgumentException("command required");
    if (userRepository.findByEmail(new Email(cmd.email())).isPresent())
        throw new EmailAlreadyInUseException(cmd.email());
    ...
}
```

## SOLID

- **S**: one reason to change per class.
- **O**: extend via new implementations of ports, not by editing existing logic.
- **L**: subtypes honor the contract of their interface.
- **I**: small, focused ports (`PasswordHasher`, `TokenGenerator`) over fat interfaces.
- **D**: depend on abstractions (ports), inject implementations from the outside.

## Other

- Prefer immutability: `final` fields, `record`s for data, no setters where avoidable.
- Avoid `null` in return values — use `Optional`. Validate inputs at boundaries.
- Throw specific exceptions; never swallow them silently. Use a logger, never `printStackTrace`/`System.out`.
- No dead code, no commented-out blocks. Comments explain **why**, not what.
- Keep formatting consistent; let the build's formatter/linter enforce style.
